   # The `for` loop `for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--)` uses `size_t`, which is an unsigned type.
   # For a vector of size 3, `v.size() - 1` is 2.
   # i values: 2, 1, 0.
   # When i is 0, the body `std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);` runs once more for i=0.
   # Then the decrement `i--` occurs, setting `i` to `ULONG_MAX`.
   # The condition `i >= 0` is checked, which is true because `i` is unsigned.
   # The loop body executes again for `i = ULONG_MAX`, leading to a buffer overflow as `v[ULONG_MAX]` is accessed.

   
   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: The loop counter `i` is declared as a `size_t` (an
   unsigned integer type), making the loop condition `i >= 0` always evaluate to
   true. When the loop finishes processing the element at index 0 and decrements
   `i` (which becomes `size_t`'s maximum value), the loop condition remains true
   and proceeds to access `v[i]` at an out-of-bounds index, causing a memory
   access error.
   
   LOCAL FIX: A common fix is to change the loop condition to account for the
   unsigned nature of the counter, for example by checking `i !=
   static_cast<size_t>(-1)` or by using a signed integer for the index while
   keeping it within the valid bounds of the vector. A safer approach is to use
   a `while` loop or change the condition:
   ```cpp
   for (size_t i = v.size(); i-- > 0; ) {
       std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
   }
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: To prevent this entire class of bugs, prefer using C++ Standard
   Library features such as `std::reverse_iterator` or
   `std::ranges::views::reverse` (if available, e.g., C++20). These abstractions
   clearly express the intent of iterating in reverse without requiring manual
   management of loop counter indices, thus guaranteeing safety and improving
   code readability.
